<subSubSection box="[199,1112,657,683]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,152,791]" box="[199,1112,657,683]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,657,683]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a combination of Latin terms 
<emphasis box="[926,977,657,683]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">pub-</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[1032,1105,658,683]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">pennis</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="357" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,152,791]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,692,719]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species shares a similar dorsal color pattern with 
<taxonomicName authority="Weise" authorityName="Weise, H" authorityYear="1889" box="[1011,1289,693,719]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Exomis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="357" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="peplopteroides">
<emphasis box="[1011,1209,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">E. peplopteroides</emphasis>
Weise
</taxonomicName>
, but the new species can be well defined by the elytra clothed with short pale pubescence and by the aedeagus with the basal 3/4 paler and less sclerotized than the apical quarter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
